Why use R?

  • Because it can do more… but most of what I like are the advanced features.

  • Data Exploration
  • Plotting
  • Reproducability

  • Advanced features

    …but it can be a bit scary at the start.

I've been using R for a few years and I find it extremely useful for a variety of different tasks and I now rarely use Excel and almost never open up SPSS.

So why do I like it?

Because I can do so much more with it and do it faster…

But here are a few concrete examples of how it could help you.

Getting started can be a challenge. R was the language of choice for my data science course so I was highly motivated, and given good tuition, to get me over that initial learning curve. So hopefully this presentation is super compelling…

Exploratory Data Analysis - WIM

Weigh in Motion (WIM) data for a site in rural South Australia.


wim <- read.csv("WiM_Formatted.csv")

names(wim)

hist(wim$GCM)

summary(wim$GCM)

wim[ wim$GCM > 100, "Config" ]





  • WIM = Weigh in Motion. A device that measures a vehicles mass as it drivers over it.

  • wim <- read.csv("WiM_Formatted.csv")

  • names(wim)

  • hist(wim$GCM)

  • hist(wim$GCM, 75, xlab="Vehicle Mass (tonnes)", main="Vehicles Mass Histogram")

  • summary(wim$GCM)

  • wim[ wim$GCM > 100, "Config" ]

Exploratory Data Analysis - WIM

Steer axle mass on 123 heavy vehicles can be used to determine if the site is measuring correctly.


Config123 <- wim[ wim$Config == 123, ]

hist(Config123$AXMASS1)






Now WIM sites actually measure individual axle groups.

  • Config123 <- wim[ wim$Config == 123, ]

  • hist(Config123$AXMASS1)

  • hist(Config123$AXMASS1, 40, freq=FALSE, main="Config 123 Axle Grp 1 Histogram", xlab="Axle Group 1 Mass (tonnes)", cex.lab=1.4, cex.axis=1.4)

  • lines(density123, lwd=1.5)

  • density123<-density(Config123$AXMASS1)

  • round(density123\(x[ which.max(density123\)y) ], 3)

Plotting - Cars

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=qsec, colour=as.factor(cyl))) +
    geom_point() +
    facet_wrap("am")

  • ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=qsec)) + geom_point()

  • ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=qsec, colour=as.factor(cyl))) + geom_point() + facet_wrap("am")

  • ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=qsec, colour=as.factor(cyl))) + geom_point() + facet_wrap("am", labeller = labeller(am = c("0"="Auto", "1"="Manual"))) + labs(x = "Gross horsepower", y = "Quarter mile time (seconds)", colour="No. Cyl")

  • g <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=qsec, colour=as.factor(cyl))) + geom_point() + labs(x = "Gross horsepower", y = "Quarter mile time (seconds)", colour="No. Cyl")

Plotting - Custom Graphics

While simple is good, sometimes it is important to look at a lot of data at once which is why visualisation is so important. This graph takes quite a while to get your head around but it was created for a very specific purpose. I was working on a project on Kaggle investigating Kiva micro-loan data and I just couldn't get my head around the data, there were so many seemingly conflicting variables. This graph took 4 of those variables and brought a lot of clarity to what was going on… once you get used to reading it.

I don't want to dig into this too much but it is possible to develop complex custom visualisations when you need them.

New Plotting Package - ggpubr

library(ggpubr)

ggscatter(DF, x="wt", y="mpg", color="cyl", palette = "jco", label = "name", repel = TRUE)

Data Manipulation

# Subset / Filter
DF[DF$carb>=6,]

# Merge / Join
CYL_NM <- data.frame( cyl=c(4,6,8), cyl_nm=c("four", "six", "eight") )
merge( DF, CYL_NM, by="cyl" )

# Aggregate
aggregate( .~cyl, data=mtcars, FUN=mean )

# Loop
for( i in 1:5 ) { print( i ) }

# Function
fun1 <- function(x) { x^2 + 2*x + 4 }
fun1(5)
  • DF[DF$wt<=4,]
  • DF[DF\(carb>=6 & DF\)wt<=4,]

Reproducability

Replication of experiments is the cornerstone of science, but replication isn't always possible. Reproducability ensures that data methodology of an analysis is record and can be tested.

Some ways to ensure reproducibility are:

  • Scripting
  • Incorporating instructions and explinations
  • Providing data
  • scripting, including markdown documents like this that allow lots of documentation to go with the code

Comparison - strengths

Excel

  • Data entry
  • Looking at data values
  • Works for small data
  • Lower barrier of entry

R

  • Visualisations
  • Summaries
  • Big datasets
  • Reproducible resarch


Tableau

  • Interactive visualisation
  • Large datasets
  • Ease of use

Python

  • As per R
  • Broader applications
  • Slightly bigger learning curve
